award-winning PBS Discovery

00:01:42.720 --> 00:01:44.580
Channel show, "Bill
Nye, the Science Guy"--

00:01:44.580 --> 00:01:45.538
[APPLAUSE AND CHEERING]

00:01:45.538 --> 00:01:47.610
--give it up for that--

00:01:47.610 --> 00:01:51.300
and the current host of
Netflix show "Bill Nye Saves

00:01:51.300 --> 00:01:54.360
the World-- give
it up for that--

00:01:54.360 --> 00:01:58.350
Bill is a science educator,
mechanical engineer, and New

00:01:58.350 --> 00:02:00.880
York Times best-selling author.

00:02:00.880 --> 00:02:03.300
He's also the CEO of
the Planetary Society,

00:02:03.300 --> 00:02:06.840
that we'll talk about, and holds
a BS in mechanical engineering

00:02:06.840 --> 00:02:09.284
from Cornell, and has
several doctorate degrees.

00:02:09.284 --> 00:02:12.480
So let's give a warm
introduction of welcome

00:02:12.480 --> 00:02:13.780
to Bill Nye.

00:02:13.780 --> 00:02:14.676
[APPLAUSE]

00:02:14.676 --> 00:02:15.800
BILL NYE: Thank you, Malik.

00:02:15.800 --> 00:02:16.770
Thank you.

00:02:16.770 --> 00:02:18.585
Is there any time left?

00:02:18.585 --> 00:02:19.710
MALIK DUCARD: That's right.

00:02:19.710 --> 00:02:21.210
That's right.

00:02:21.210 --> 00:02:25.020
So I had the opportunity to
read your book, "Everything

00:02:25.020 --> 00:02:27.244
All At Once," and loved it.

00:02:27.244 --> 00:02:28.410
BILL NYE: I appreciate that.

00:02:28.410 --> 00:02:30.210
You know, a lot of times,
you get interviewed,

00:02:30.210 --> 00:02:31.505
and they haven't read the book.

00:02:31.505 --> 00:02:32.500
So that's nice.

00:02:32.500 --> 00:02:33.000
Thank you.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:34.650
MALIK DUCARD: I have
read it, cover to cover.

00:02:34.650 --> 00:02:36.540
BILL NYE: And these are your
people here, it looks like.

00:02:36.540 --> 00:02:38.748
MALIK DUCARD: These are my
people, my kids, and wife.

00:02:38.748 --> 00:02:40.337
BILL NYE: They're
not in school today.

00:02:40.337 --> 00:02:41.291
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:41.291 --> 00:02:43.596
Well, it's July, I guess.

00:02:43.596 --> 00:02:44.970
MALIK DUCARD: So
can you tell us,

00:02:44.970 --> 00:02:47.970
what does everything
all at once mean?

00:02:47.970 --> 00:02:51.760
BILL NYE: So we have a great
many problems facing humankind.

00:02:51.760 --> 00:02:57.540
We have-- oh, when I
was in grade school,

00:02:57.540 --> 00:03:00.330
there were three billion
people in the world.

00:03:00.330 --> 00:03:02.730
Now there are
almost 7.4 billion.

00:03:02.730 --> 00:03:05.010
By 2050, there
certainly will be 9,

00:03:05.010 --> 00:03:07.792
but there may be
10 billion people.

00:03:07.792 --> 00:03:09.750
And they're all going to
want access to Google.

00:03:09.750 --> 00:03:11.970
They're all going to
want to live the way we

00:03:11.970 --> 00:03:14.064
live in the developed world.

00:03:14.064 --> 00:03:15.480
So this means we've
got to provide

00:03:15.480 --> 00:03:19.350
clean water, reliable,
renewably-produced electricity,

00:03:19.350 --> 00:03:22.540
and access to the
internet to everybody.

00:03:22.540 --> 00:03:23.790
And that's a big job.

00:03:23.790 --> 00:03:27.692
So we got to do
everything all at once.

00:03:27.692 --> 00:03:29.560
Let's go.

00:03:29.560 --> 00:03:33.610
And so along this line,
I just tell everybody,

00:03:33.610 --> 00:03:35.800
I'm not much for multitasking.

00:03:35.800 --> 00:03:39.250
I think that really, as much
as I love all the young people,

00:03:39.250 --> 00:03:41.680
I think there really
isn't any such thing.

00:03:41.680 --> 00:03:44.020
Instead, you've got to keep
in mind everything that

00:03:44.020 --> 00:03:48.730
has to be done as you
accomplish each task.

00:03:48.730 --> 00:03:50.410
Does that help?

00:03:50.410 --> 00:03:53.820
Plus, it's a catchy
title, people.

00:03:53.820 --> 00:03:55.110
It's catchy.

00:03:55.110 --> 00:03:56.610
I'm caught.

00:03:56.610 --> 00:03:57.600
MALIK DUCARD: Yeah.

00:03:57.600 --> 00:04:01.230
All right, in reading
this book, it almost

00:04:01.230 --> 00:04:04.650
seemed like it was a manifesto.

00:04:04.650 --> 00:04:05.940
BILL NYE: Yes.

00:04:05.940 --> 00:04:06.845
The nerd manifesto.

00:04:06.845 --> 00:04:08.237
MALIK DUCARD: A nerd manifesto.

00:04:08.237 --> 00:04:08.820
BILL NYE: Yes.

00:04:08.820 --> 00:04:10.530
MALIK DUCARD: That's right.

00:04:10.530 --> 00:04:11.730
BILL NYE: Do it this way.

00:04:11.730 --> 00:04:15.270
MALIK DUCARD: It's
an activist book.

00:04:15.270 --> 00:04:19.802
Where does that come from,
and what are you acting on?

00:04:19.802 --> 00:04:21.010
BILL NYE: There's two things.

00:04:21.010 --> 00:04:23.790
Everybody's responsible
for his or her own actions.

00:04:23.790 --> 00:04:25.374
This is something
my dad would say.

00:04:25.374 --> 00:04:27.540
And then you want to leave
the world better than you

00:04:27.540 --> 00:04:29.880
found that, if you can.

00:04:29.880 --> 00:04:32.530
And if we don't
hustle, we're going

00:04:32.530 --> 00:04:34.750
to leave the world a lot
worse than we found it.

00:04:34.750 --> 00:04:36.610
And so we got to get to work.

00:04:36.610 --> 00:04:38.050
So that's why I'm an activist.

00:04:38.050 --> 00:04:40.020
I mean, I guess.

00:04:40.020 --> 00:04:42.750
When it comes to things
like scientific literacy,

00:04:42.750 --> 00:04:46.590
that seems like an obvious
thing to be in favor of,

00:04:46.590 --> 00:04:51.580
because it enables companies
like this to change the world.

00:04:51.580 --> 00:04:55.350
And it also enables a country
like the United States

00:04:55.350 --> 00:04:57.870
to remain competitive
economically,

00:04:57.870 --> 00:05:01.390
because innovation, which is
what you guys are all about.

00:05:01.390 --> 00:05:05.460
But then, you would think
that climate change would not

00:05:05.460 --> 00:05:08.670
be anything to argue about.

00:05:08.670 --> 00:05:10.530
It would be something
to get to work on.

00:05:10.530 --> 00:05:14.430
Yet, we have this
amazing contingent

00:05:14.430 --> 00:05:16.140
or a segment of
our society that's

00:05:16.140 --> 00:05:18.750
in denial about
climate change, because

00:05:18.750 --> 00:05:22.920
of the success of
the climate deniers.

00:05:22.920 --> 00:05:24.240
They've been so influential.

00:05:24.240 --> 00:05:26.590
It's really, it's
really amazing.

00:05:26.590 --> 00:05:28.410
So that's why I wrote this book.

00:05:28.410 --> 00:05:29.690
Let's go.

00:05:29.690 --> 00:05:30.870
MALIK DUCARD: That's right.

00:05:30.870 --> 00:05:31.460
BILL NYE: When are we done?

00:05:31.460 --> 00:05:32.940
At 1 o'clock, you guys will be--

00:05:32.940 --> 00:05:34.710
you'll have it all
set by 1:30 or--

00:05:34.710 --> 00:05:35.910
MALIK DUCARD: We'll
have all the answers.

00:05:35.910 --> 00:05:37.868
BILL NYE: --a quarter to
2:00, it will be done.

00:05:37.868 --> 00:05:40.650
MALIK DUCARD: And why do you
think that there are so many

00:05:40.650 --> 00:05:41.297
deniers?

00:05:41.297 --> 00:05:43.380
BILL NYE: Oh, because of
the fossil fuel industry.

00:05:43.380 --> 00:05:45.950
I mean, that's not
rocket surgery, you guys.

00:05:45.950 --> 00:05:48.690
The fossil fuel
industry is just really

00:05:48.690 --> 00:05:51.780
throwing money at the problem
to influence their congressmen

00:05:51.780 --> 00:05:56.970
representatives, not just
tactically, by sending

00:05:56.970 --> 00:05:59.880
specious materials and stuff
to the congressional staff,

00:05:59.880 --> 00:06:02.940
but strategically,
working statewide

00:06:02.940 --> 00:06:06.420
or commonwealth wide, in
Kentucky, Tennessee, and so on,

00:06:06.420 --> 00:06:09.019
to the point where
it's no trouble

00:06:09.019 --> 00:06:10.560
at all to meet people
who go, well, I

00:06:10.560 --> 00:06:12.660
don't know if climate
change is really happening.

00:06:12.660 --> 00:06:15.330
Yeah, it really is.

00:06:15.330 --> 00:06:19.150
So it's a big problem, and it's
almost unique to the United

00:06:19.150 --> 00:06:19.770
States.

00:06:19.770 --> 00:06:22.800
There's very few climate
deniers in other-- in the UK,

00:06:22.800 --> 00:06:24.750
there's quite a few, I guess.

00:06:24.750 --> 00:06:28.710
But at the recent summit of
the 20 largest economies,

00:06:28.710 --> 00:06:30.605
the United States was isolated.

00:06:30.605 --> 00:06:33.900
It doesn't want to participate
in the Paris agreement,

00:06:33.900 --> 00:06:35.430
and so on.

00:06:35.430 --> 00:06:38.050
One word for it would be silly.

00:06:38.050 --> 00:06:40.092
But another one would
be deeply concerning.

00:06:40.092 --> 00:06:40.800
That's two words.

00:06:40.800 --> 00:06:41.700
But it's like that.

00:06:41.700 --> 00:06:42.710
It's like that.

00:06:42.710 --> 00:06:45.330
MALIK DUCARD: And what
do you think the path is?

00:06:45.330 --> 00:06:48.150
There's the science
behind the reality,

00:06:48.150 --> 00:06:50.760
but then there's
also the reality

00:06:50.760 --> 00:06:53.010
of politics, the social
engineering, that

00:06:53.010 --> 00:06:55.320
maybe needs to be factored in.

00:06:55.320 --> 00:06:57.780
How do we get to the
place that we need to be?

00:06:57.780 --> 00:07:01.980
BILL NYE: Well, climate
deniers, in this one case,

00:07:01.980 --> 00:07:06.750
not so much anti-vaxxers, but
climate deniers are almost

00:07:06.750 --> 00:07:09.280
universally old.

00:07:09.280 --> 00:07:13.270
They're almost all older
people, over 50 years, 60,

00:07:13.270 --> 00:07:17.830
70 years old, people who
control a lot of the money.

00:07:17.830 --> 00:07:23.890
And when those people age
out, as the saying goes--

00:07:23.890 --> 00:07:28.470
the other expression
for that is die--

00:07:28.470 --> 00:07:30.000
then the young people--

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:32.436
if you've ever seen the map--
maybe you guys generated it.

00:07:32.436 --> 00:07:33.360
It was Survey Monkey.

00:07:33.360 --> 00:07:36.900
There is a map of the electoral
college of only millennials

00:07:36.900 --> 00:07:40.440
that voted, and
it's overwhelmingly

00:07:40.440 --> 00:07:44.670
the other way on social issues,
especially climate change.

00:07:44.670 --> 00:07:47.970
So I think climate
change deniers, who

00:07:47.970 --> 00:07:51.930
are affiliated with the
conservative parties,

00:07:51.930 --> 00:07:53.470
are very much aware of that.

00:07:53.470 --> 00:07:57.600
And so there's a big hustle to
get very conservative judges

00:07:57.600 --> 00:07:59.670
put in place in
the Supreme Court

00:07:59.670 --> 00:08:02.490
and to maintain this
denial as long as possible,

00:08:02.490 --> 00:08:05.010
to get as many regulations
turned over as possible,

00:08:05.010 --> 00:08:06.640
as quickly as possible.

00:08:06.640 --> 00:08:09.960
But when you guys get
to be the majority

00:08:09.960 --> 00:08:13.090
of the voting of
the electorate, this

00:08:13.090 --> 00:08:15.120
will all have to be re-reversed.

00:08:15.120 --> 00:08:15.900
And it'll happen.

00:08:15.900 --> 00:08:21.150
But for people like
me, my life will

00:08:21.150 --> 00:08:23.850
suck a little bit near
the end, but you guys,

00:08:23.850 --> 00:08:25.980
your lives will
really suck, because--

00:08:25.980 --> 00:08:27.540
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:27.540 --> 00:08:33.100
once the carbon dioxide, methane
stuff are in the atmosphere,

00:08:33.100 --> 00:08:34.380
you just don't get them out.

00:08:34.380 --> 00:08:36.460
Carbon dioxide lasts a
couple hundred years.

00:08:36.460 --> 00:08:39.630
Its cycle is about
five years, but it

00:08:39.630 --> 00:08:41.711
gets replaced by another
carbon dioxide molecule.

00:08:41.711 --> 00:08:43.919
And that's going to go on
for a couple hundred years.

00:08:43.919 --> 00:08:47.337
The analogy is you have
a roast in the oven

00:08:47.337 --> 00:08:48.920
or a turkey in the
over, or whatever--

00:08:48.920 --> 00:08:51.610
I know, OK, this is
use your imagination,

00:08:51.610 --> 00:08:52.810
vegans, just imagine.

00:08:52.810 --> 00:08:55.744
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:55.744 --> 00:08:57.160
After you take it
out of the oven,

00:08:57.160 --> 00:08:58.600
the heat is still
working its way

00:08:58.600 --> 00:09:00.070
into the middle for a long time.

00:09:00.070 --> 00:09:03.220
And that's what's going
to happen to the earth.

00:09:03.220 --> 00:09:05.920
So we want to get to work on
climate change as fast we can.

00:09:05.920 --> 00:09:06.760
MALIK DUCARD: How
much time do we have?

00:09:06.760 --> 00:09:08.593
BILL NYE: Well, everybody
argues about that,

00:09:08.593 --> 00:09:11.080
that people will be
around indefinitely.

00:09:11.080 --> 00:09:12.020
You can't kill humans.

00:09:12.020 --> 00:09:13.060
They're crazy.

00:09:13.060 --> 00:09:16.630
But you want to have the
highest quality of life

00:09:16.630 --> 00:09:20.230
for as many people as possible.

00:09:20.230 --> 00:09:22.030
Santa Monica beach is cool.

00:09:22.030 --> 00:09:22.750
Why bury it?

00:09:22.750 --> 00:09:24.490
Why put it under water?

00:09:24.490 --> 00:09:25.640
Come on.

00:09:25.640 --> 00:09:27.102
Let's keep it.

00:09:27.102 --> 00:09:29.200
MALIK DUCARD: Can I read
a passage from your book?

00:09:29.200 --> 00:09:30.150
BILL NYE: What if I said no?

00:09:30.150 --> 00:09:30.960
What would that do?

00:09:30.960 --> 00:09:31.310
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:31.310 --> 00:09:32.270
MALIK DUCARD: I'd go
to the next question.

00:09:32.270 --> 00:09:33.811
BILL NYE: Read the
whole thing, yeah.

00:09:33.811 --> 00:09:34.660
Turn it up loud.

00:09:34.660 --> 00:09:36.040
Come on, Malik.

00:09:36.040 --> 00:09:38.002
Let them hear you outside.

00:09:38.002 --> 00:09:39.600
Blow the roof off the dump.

00:09:39.600 --> 00:09:40.900
Let's go.

00:09:40.900 --> 00:09:41.740
Blast it.

00:09:41.740 --> 00:09:44.890
MALIK DUCARD: So you
write, "A lot of what

00:09:44.890 --> 00:09:47.210
I've done over the
past four decades,

00:09:47.210 --> 00:09:49.630
including writing the book
that you're reading now,

00:09:49.630 --> 00:09:52.690
was inspired by the need to
help people understand what it

00:09:52.690 --> 00:09:55.450
means to be a global species.

00:09:55.450 --> 00:09:58.900
The challenge is taking
responsibility for our actions,

00:09:58.900 --> 00:10:01.360
assuming deliberate
control of the change.

00:10:01.360 --> 00:10:02.980
We're all in this together.

00:10:02.980 --> 00:10:06.260
Nerds don't give up when
there's a problem to be solved.

00:10:06.260 --> 00:10:08.890
And so I've kept working
on my climate message,

00:10:08.890 --> 00:10:12.700
redoubling my efforts to
try everything all at once."

00:10:12.700 --> 00:10:13.550
BILL NYE: Yes!

00:10:13.550 --> 00:10:14.620
MALIK DUCARD: What
have you been doing?

00:10:14.620 --> 00:10:15.370
BILL NYE: Brilliant.

00:10:15.370 --> 00:10:16.203
MALIK DUCARD: It is.

00:10:16.203 --> 00:10:17.200
It is.

00:10:17.200 --> 00:10:18.160
And thank you for that.

00:10:18.160 --> 00:10:20.620
And what have you been
doing all at once?

00:10:20.620 --> 00:10:22.160
This has really been your life.

00:10:22.160 --> 00:10:23.380
BILL NYE: Well, I come here.

00:10:23.380 --> 00:10:26.200
I wrote another book,
which takes time.

00:10:26.200 --> 00:10:29.140
I don't know if you've tried it.

00:10:29.140 --> 00:10:31.220
And I go to college campuses.

00:10:31.220 --> 00:10:31.760
I speak.

00:10:31.760 --> 00:10:33.670
I go to US Congress.

00:10:33.670 --> 00:10:35.710
I go to the
Astronautical Congress,

00:10:35.710 --> 00:10:38.650
which is a huge party
of rocket people.

00:10:38.650 --> 00:10:42.940
And we talk about climate
change and Bill's big three--

00:10:42.940 --> 00:10:45.730
clean water, renewable
electricity, and access

00:10:45.730 --> 00:10:47.390
to the internet.

00:10:47.390 --> 00:10:50.020
And for example, at the
Astronautical Congress,

00:10:50.020 --> 00:10:52.510
to provide access to the
internet in the developing

00:10:52.510 --> 00:10:55.090
world will almost
certainly involve

00:10:55.090 --> 00:10:59.800
what we call space assets, what
other people call satellites.

00:10:59.800 --> 00:11:02.950
And they're going to have
to be in low-earth orbit,

00:11:02.950 --> 00:11:04.990
a constellation of a
few hundred of them.

00:11:04.990 --> 00:11:09.460
