00:57:06.920 --> 00:57:09.920
And I guess I find that,
I don't know, sometimes,

00:57:09.920 --> 00:57:13.820
I'll argue with people who
I radically disagree with.

00:57:13.820 --> 00:57:17.450
And it quickly becomes
clear that in no way

00:57:17.450 --> 00:57:19.670
is it going to be fruitful.

00:57:19.670 --> 00:57:21.830
For example, I know
all these people

00:57:21.830 --> 00:57:24.050
who are right-wing,
populist extremists

00:57:24.050 --> 00:57:25.910
from my hometown in Tennessee.

00:57:25.910 --> 00:57:28.010
And you talk to them
about immigration.

00:57:28.010 --> 00:57:30.110
And you're like, well,
what about the human cost

00:57:30.110 --> 00:57:32.030
of that ridiculous
policy you're proposing?

00:57:32.030 --> 00:57:34.488
And they're like, oh, yeah,
well, what about the human cost

00:57:34.488 --> 00:57:36.890
of what Hillary
Clinton did in Libya?

00:57:36.890 --> 00:57:38.810
And I'm just curious.

00:57:38.810 --> 00:57:40.580
To what extent do
you think it's worth

00:57:40.580 --> 00:57:43.517
engaging with people with
whom you radically disagree?

00:57:43.517 --> 00:57:45.350
BILL NYE: Well, I think
it's worth engaging.

00:57:45.350 --> 00:57:49.490
What happens, it's wherever
the cities are big enough

00:57:49.490 --> 00:57:52.190
to have people cross
paths, they get

00:57:52.190 --> 00:57:55.970
over this immigration thing.

00:57:55.970 --> 00:57:58.816
I think that'll
shake itself out.

00:57:58.816 --> 00:58:01.820
The smaller-- like St.
Louis is an interior city.

00:58:01.820 --> 00:58:03.410
It's not a coastal city.

00:58:03.410 --> 00:58:06.170
Minneapolis is not
a coastal city.

00:58:06.170 --> 00:58:08.660
But you'll find that
the people have lawsuits

00:58:08.660 --> 00:58:12.710
or the state attorney
generals have lawsuits

00:58:12.710 --> 00:58:16.730
against this policy, because
the big cities have diversity.

00:58:16.730 --> 00:58:18.420
And you do business
with your neighbors,

00:58:18.420 --> 00:58:21.770
and you just-- my understanding
is you get over it.

00:58:21.770 --> 00:58:26.300
So you just challenge
your friends to travel.

00:58:26.300 --> 00:58:27.280
You go to New York.

00:58:27.280 --> 00:58:29.060
It's a real place.

00:58:29.060 --> 00:58:31.250
There are fewer murders
per day in New York

00:58:31.250 --> 00:58:33.080
than any major
metropolitan city,

00:58:33.080 --> 00:58:37.220
because the city
freaked out after 9/11.

00:58:37.220 --> 00:58:39.470
There's a cop on every corner.

00:58:39.470 --> 00:58:40.999
And you never get
lost in New York,

00:58:40.999 --> 00:58:43.540
because you can ask directions
of all the cops on the corner.

00:58:43.540 --> 00:58:45.650
It's fabulous.

00:58:45.650 --> 00:58:47.900
And encourage them
to go to Paris

00:58:47.900 --> 00:58:49.360
and see what people are like.

00:58:49.360 --> 00:58:52.280
Wow, people eat food, cool.

00:58:52.280 --> 00:58:53.300
Did not know that.

00:58:53.300 --> 00:58:58.340
And I think it's just
we got to get along.

00:58:58.340 --> 00:59:03.620
What you all do at Google
is democratize the internet,

00:59:03.620 --> 00:59:06.560
you know, democratize
interaction,

00:59:06.560 --> 00:59:07.620
social interaction.

00:59:07.620 --> 00:59:09.890
So it's a long process.

00:59:09.890 --> 00:59:13.100
But I encourage you to
engage people about anything

00:59:13.100 --> 00:59:14.310
like that.

00:59:14.310 --> 00:59:16.940
And as far as immigration
policies, it is--

00:59:19.560 --> 00:59:24.940
OK, no aunts or uncles, no
grandparents, can go-- really?

00:59:24.940 --> 00:59:26.530
Have you thought this through?

00:59:26.530 --> 00:59:28.310
So we'll see what happens.

00:59:28.310 --> 00:59:31.390
I don't think that
policy will last.

00:59:31.390 --> 00:59:34.550
Because the court system,
I think, is robust enough.

00:59:34.550 --> 00:59:36.670
But we'll see what happens.

00:59:36.670 --> 00:59:39.890
I tell everybody-- I
remember when Nixon resigned.

00:59:39.890 --> 00:59:41.470
I'm that old.

00:59:41.470 --> 00:59:44.560
It took a year and a
half for all that stuff

00:59:44.560 --> 00:59:45.560
to catch up with him.

00:59:45.560 --> 00:59:49.015
So we'll see what happens
in the coming months.

00:59:49.015 --> 00:59:51.985
[LAUGHTER]

00:59:51.985 --> 00:59:53.965
[APPLAUSE]

00:59:53.965 --> 00:59:56.110
Well, maybe nothing will happen.

00:59:56.110 --> 00:59:57.814
I mean, it's not my idea.

00:59:57.814 --> 00:59:59.230
MALIK DUCARD: Can
you talk quickly

00:59:59.230 --> 01:00:02.050
about your national
service idea?

01:00:02.050 --> 01:00:04.970
BILL NYE: Oh yeah, my national
service idea-- this is great.

01:00:04.970 --> 01:00:07.990
So Bill, you chose not
to join the military,

01:00:07.990 --> 01:00:09.130
and you've got an opinion?

01:00:09.130 --> 01:00:10.900
Yeah!

01:00:10.900 --> 01:00:16.270
So people my age, the reason
I did not go to Vietnam

01:00:16.270 --> 01:00:20.020
was because, basically,
I'm six months too young.

01:00:20.020 --> 01:00:23.930
I missed getting
drafted by six months.

01:00:23.930 --> 01:00:28.155
I had to register for the draft,
and your height and weight

01:00:28.155 --> 01:00:28.780
and everything.

01:00:28.780 --> 01:00:31.430
And you get ready to
be enlisted, and stuff.

01:00:31.430 --> 01:00:35.740
But then, the draft was
abolished right before.

01:00:35.740 --> 01:00:36.846
I was born in November.

01:00:36.846 --> 01:00:38.470
I went to kindergarten
when I was four.

01:00:38.470 --> 01:00:44.260
So I didn't turn 18 till
my senior in high school.

01:00:44.260 --> 01:00:46.360
So I missed the draft
by a few months.

01:00:46.360 --> 01:00:49.240
But my older brother's
friends were deeply

01:00:49.240 --> 01:00:52.210
affected by the Vietnam
War in a bad way.

01:00:52.210 --> 01:00:54.850
But nevertheless, because
of my parents' experience

01:00:54.850 --> 01:00:58.720
with the military, my dad
was, many years later,

01:00:58.720 --> 01:01:01.660
declared a veteran, because
they had served with Marines

01:01:01.660 --> 01:01:05.150
and prisoner of war camp.

01:01:05.150 --> 01:01:08.500
I looked into Air Force ROTC.

01:01:08.500 --> 01:01:10.030
And I wanted to fly jets.

01:01:10.030 --> 01:01:11.950
I thought that would be cool.

01:01:11.950 --> 01:01:14.490
I went to get my
physical, and there

01:01:14.490 --> 01:01:16.610
were a bunch of
pilots sitting there

01:01:16.610 --> 01:01:19.480
in an Air Force Base
in Rome, New York,

01:01:19.480 --> 01:01:24.010
for you rural New York buffs.

01:01:24.010 --> 01:01:26.140
And I said, how often
do you guys fly?

01:01:26.140 --> 01:01:30.207
Oh, every six weeks,
sometimes every two months.

01:01:30.207 --> 01:01:31.540
What do you do the rest of time?

01:01:31.540 --> 01:01:34.920
Oh, we memorize procedures.

01:01:34.920 --> 01:01:37.130
Wow.

01:01:37.130 --> 01:01:39.130
Doesn't sound like much fun.

01:01:39.130 --> 01:01:42.360
So I did not join the military.

01:01:42.360 --> 01:01:44.730
But if I had been required
to, I certainly would have.

01:01:44.730 --> 01:01:48.570
So my proposal is that we
have a national service

01:01:48.570 --> 01:01:52.470
akin to the Americorp,
akin to the Peace Corps,

01:01:52.470 --> 01:01:54.150
where everybody had to join.

01:01:54.150 --> 01:01:57.660
So in my parents' day,
everybody my parents' age,

01:01:57.660 --> 01:01:59.880
when they would meet
at any situation--

01:01:59.880 --> 01:02:04.409
waiting in line at the grocery
store, when they would go out

01:02:04.409 --> 01:02:05.950
dancing, when they'd
go out to dinner

01:02:05.950 --> 01:02:10.350
at a restaurant, when they'd
pick up kids at school-- what

01:02:10.350 --> 01:02:13.050
they all talked about was
what they did during the war,

01:02:13.050 --> 01:02:13.680
World War II.

01:02:13.680 --> 01:02:16.410
Because this thing
was such a big deal,

01:02:16.410 --> 01:02:18.510
it bound everybody together.

01:02:18.510 --> 01:02:21.857
People of all faiths,
of all ancestry,

01:02:21.857 --> 01:02:23.190
were all in this thing together.

01:02:23.190 --> 01:02:28.050
So my proposal is that we have
a national service that you have

01:02:28.050 --> 01:02:31.410
to complete before you turn 26.

01:02:31.410 --> 01:02:33.490
And then we would
all be involved.

01:02:33.490 --> 01:02:34.950
And if you join
the military, that

01:02:34.950 --> 01:02:37.280
would count, of course,
for your national service.

01:02:37.280 --> 01:02:40.890
It would be involved here
domestically or maybe overseas,

01:02:40.890 --> 01:02:42.350
all in this thing together.

01:02:42.350 --> 01:02:45.240
And yes, yes, crazy
Uncle Bill, it

01:02:45.240 --> 01:02:47.430
would have to be paid
for with tax dollars.

01:02:47.430 --> 01:02:50.070
Ahh, ahhh-ahh-ahh!

01:02:50.070 --> 01:02:52.480
But we would get
infrastructure, Bill.

01:02:52.480 --> 01:02:56.490
We would get schools connected
to the internet, for example.

01:02:56.490 --> 01:02:58.300
And everybody would
be required to do it,

01:02:58.300 --> 01:03:01.000
and we'd all take it for
granted that we had to do it.

01:03:01.000 --> 01:03:05.640
And I think it would bind
us together and ultimately,

01:03:05.640 --> 01:03:06.570
save money.

01:03:06.570 --> 01:03:09.330
And we wouldn't have this
red state, blue state,

01:03:09.330 --> 01:03:11.610
horrible division,
that we're nurturing

01:03:11.610 --> 01:03:14.080
or we're end up with right now.

01:03:14.080 --> 01:03:15.240
And it's a crazy idea.

01:03:15.240 --> 01:03:19.620
But the idea is, if you wanted
to, you could finish college,

01:03:19.620 --> 01:03:23.160
undergraduate, before you
did your national service.

01:03:23.160 --> 01:03:26.400
If you, like my dad, didn't
think law school sounded

01:03:26.400 --> 01:03:29.352
like all that much fun, you
would do your national service

01:03:29.352 --> 01:03:30.060
right after that.

01:03:30.060 --> 01:03:32.730
If you were obsessed and crazy,
like a few of you are crazy,

01:03:32.730 --> 01:03:36.330
just are interested in
your academic success,

01:03:36.330 --> 01:03:39.720
and you wanted to
get your PhD, you

01:03:39.720 --> 01:03:42.390
would take your national service
after you got your masters

01:03:42.390 --> 01:03:44.190
degree, before you
went back for your PhD.

01:03:44.190 --> 01:03:45.610
That's my proposal.

01:03:45.610 --> 01:03:47.190
Bill, that'll never fly.

01:03:47.190 --> 01:03:48.460
Everybody hates each other.

01:03:48.460 --> 01:03:50.293
We don't want to spend
any more tax dollars.

01:03:50.293 --> 01:03:51.270
I know, OK.

01:03:51.270 --> 01:03:55.110
So what if each state
had a state service?

01:03:55.110 --> 01:03:58.620
In California, state service
would put pressure on Nevada

01:03:58.620 --> 01:04:02.010
to have a Nevada state service,
and an Arizona state service.

01:04:02.010 --> 01:04:04.305
Oregon would sure as heck
put pressure on Washington

01:04:04.305 --> 01:04:06.060
to have a state service.

01:04:06.060 --> 01:04:08.780
And then maybe this could
become a national service.

01:04:08.780 --> 01:04:11.130
It's a proposal.

01:04:11.130 --> 01:04:12.630
It's a little crazy.

01:04:12.630 --> 01:04:14.760
I'm glad you asked about it.

01:04:14.760 --> 01:04:17.209
But the idea is that we'd
all have a common purpose

01:04:17.209 --> 01:04:18.750
so we wouldn't have--
you know, there

01:04:18.750 --> 01:04:24.480
was 15 minutes after 9/11, where
everybody was rah, rah, US,

01:04:24.480 --> 01:04:29.070
in a constructive way,
as horrible as that was.

01:04:29.070 --> 01:04:31.230
And so a national
service is just one

01:04:31.230 --> 01:04:32.557
of my kooky little ideas.

01:04:32.557 --> 01:04:33.390
MALIK DUCARD: Great.

01:04:33.390 --> 01:04:34.004
That's great.

